WASHINGTON - President Donald Trump's choice for national security adviser, retired Vice Admiral Robert Harward, has turned down the offer, a senior White House official said on Thursday (February 16).READ: Trump national security picks under scrutinyHarward was offered the job after Michael Flynn was fired by Trump on Monday for misleading Vice President Mike Pence over his conversations with Russia's ambassador to the United States.READ: Trump's top security man Flynn resigns over Russian contactsThe White House official said Harward cited family and financial reasons for opting not to take the job. Harward is a senior executive at Lockheed Martin.Two sources familiar with the decision said Harward turned down the job in part because he wanted to bring in his own team.That put him at odds with Trump, who had told Flynn's deputy, K.T. McFarland, that she could stay.Reuters